snippet.textDisplay:
Slight correction: 2006-2010 are the refresh "Gen2" model years.

I still enjoy my 2003 Dream Cruiser 2 (the custom orange GT one--it's a marvelous color) and my wife still enjoys her 2005 Dream Cruiser 4 (deep lava red convertible with body-color soft-top)

I love the look, love that it's unique--as you said--and love that it's polarizing (one either loves it or hates it). These cars are inexpensive to buy (I paid $21,500 for my new DC2; $24K for the DC4), inexpensive to insure (nobody steals PT Cruisers), inexpensive to maintain. In spite of the price, these have superb build quality (materials, fitment). Finally, it does have a surprising bit of utility because of its light-truck layout (flat bed), van-like layout (big open boxy space), and easily flippable and removable seats, D-rings for straps, tailgating shelf with bag-hooks.

With a few bolt-ons for the GT (Mopar Stage 1 kit: new ECU, larger fuel injectors; a better flowing exhaust, a boost controller or mess with the waste-gate actuator), one can approach 300 HRSPRS and just as many TERKS--and 90% of that torque comes in at 1200 RPM--which necessitates Michelin Pilot sneakers and a strut tower brace for grip (and their all-seasons don't really compromise: I never had to slow down in the snow-covered Colorado mountain roads with those things--even the roads with rolled-over SUVs on the side--which happens far more often than I ever thought would).

You can have the top down, 75 MPH on the freeway and have a normal conversation in a normal voice.

The only downsides are aerodynamics (.379, 25ft2 IIRC), extremely cramped engine bay and it has about the same turning radius as the Titanic.

snippet.textDisplay: God I love you guys. You show the L-bodies, the K-cars, and now the PT Cruiser. My dad has an all black PT GT with a stage 1 tune and ran 14.5! Thankfully they used the SRT4 engine so you can get pretty fast runs with them. 3 inch exhaust, Intercooler, CAI, and a stage 3 tune would probably scare a lot of people here. Now a video on the Shelby Dakota! It was the first Dakota to get a V8 unlike any truck in it's class. I own one and they're pretty special.

snippet.textDisplay: I own what is my 3rd PT! Yes, it is second gen and yes very different! The turn radius is way better though the interior is smaller and not as nice. My mother has a first gen so I drive both and am very aware of the differences. I don't know what their original target market was, however I was 45 when I bought my 1st and looked a long time to find a low mileage PT.  Found a base model continued to look until I found my Sunset Boulevard street series with only 60k to be my last PT (I am 57 now). I am slowly customizing and will probably drop a new engine and transmission in rather than buy a new car when the time comes. In a world full of cars that look alike I cruise around happily being me in my PT!
